<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="82353" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="82353">Diagnosis</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="82353">
The genus was diagnosed using the autapomorphic characters of the type species as unipectinate antennae in male and serrate antennae in female. It was identified as a cidariine genus by the venation of fore- and hind-wings and by the presence of a pair of lateral appendages to the juxta, defined as the labides. The association of 
<taxonomicName authority="Viidalepp &amp; Kostjuk, 2005" authorityName="Viidalepp &amp; Kostjuk" authorityYear="2005" class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" genus="Pljushtchia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pljushtchia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="82353" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="82353">Pljushtchia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" genus="Thera" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Thera" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="82353" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="82353">Thera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Stephens, 
<taxonomicName genus="Protothera" lsidName="Protothera" pageId="0" pageNumber="82353" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="82353">Protothera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Viidalepp and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Inoue" authorityYear="1943" class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" genus="Heterothera" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Heterothera" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="82353" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="82353">Heterothera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Inoue was supported using a cladistic analysis (
<bibRefCitation author="Viidalepp, Jaan" journalOrPublisher="European Journal of Entomology" pageId="0" pageNumber="82353" pagination="777 - 785" refId="B7668256" refString="Viidalepp, Jaan, Kostjuk, Igor, 2005. Pljushtchia prima, new moth genus and species from Tadjikistan (Lepidoptera: Geometridae). European Journal of Entomology 102 (4): 777 - 785" title="Pljushtchia prima, new moth genus and species from Tadjikistan (Lepidoptera: Geometridae)" volume="102" year="2005">Viidalepp and Kostjuk 2005</bibRefCitation>
). This analysis revealed the existence of four monophyletic groups of genera within the tribe 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Duponchel" authorityYear="1845" lsidName="" pageId="0" pageNumber="82353" rank="tribe" tribe="Cidariini">Cidariini</taxonomicName>
. 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" genus="Thera" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Thera" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="82353" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="82353">Thera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and allied genera appeared as the crown group of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Duponchel" authorityYear="1845" lsidName="" pageId="0" pageNumber="82353" rank="tribe" tribe="Cidariini">Cidariini</taxonomicName>
, characterised by the reduction of the posterior or anterior apophyses in females; the valve costa projecting distally or dorsally in male genitalia; the valve sacculus tip projecting beyond the ventral margin of valva in male genitalia and the modification or the absence of the signum in female genitalia. 
<taxonomicName authority="Viidalepp &amp; Kostjuk, 2005" authorityName="Viidalepp &amp; Kostjuk" authorityYear="2005" class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" genus="Pljushtchia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pljushtchia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="82353" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="82353">Pljushtchia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" genus="Thera" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Thera" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="82353" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="82353">Thera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in more slender wings, especially in the fore-margin of hind-wing being longer than the hind margin of the forewing.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="82353">
The 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" genus="Thera" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Thera" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="82353" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="82353">Thera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group of genera has the hind-wing discal vein twice angulate, sharing this character with its sister-group (containing of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Stephens" authorityYear="1831" class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" genus="Lampropteryx" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Lampropteryx" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="82353" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="82353">Lampropteryx</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Stephens, 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" genus="Nebula" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Nebula" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="82353" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="82353">Nebula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Bruand and others), which is otherwise diagnosed by the presence of bipartite labides or labides provided with blade-like hamuli.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
